title: For Trade:  AK47 slip-on, butt-stock spacer/pad....
postcontent: I'm letting go of another nice AK accessory I don't need anymore. This is a slip-on recoil pad/spacer, that fits on standard sized AK stocks, both wood or polymer. It adds some useful and necessary length-of-pull, recoil softening, but most imprtantly, it increases the area of the tiny butt-plate, which allows you to properly shoulder the rifle so the bottom corner of the stock isn't digging into your shoulder, and you're not forced to crank your neck sideways to sight in. (AK stocks were designed with the assumption the user would be wearing a thick,heavy parka, which automatically solves this well-known ergonomic shortcoming.) I've been a fan of these things, for years now, because they're a highly practical and functional upgrade, and are very econmomical.Look to trade for a box of pistol ammo, like 9mm,38 or 45. title: For Sale:  Scarce WWII Gustloff 98k Nazi German Mauser bcd 42 1942 K98 K98k Rifle Matching
postcontent: early production Gustloff-Werke K98k...this all-correct Mauser was produced by Gustloff for the German military in 1942. One of the last companies offered a contract by the Third Reich to produce this iconic arm, Gustloff notably maintained higher standards of build quality than the other producers throughout the war. The rifle has typical features for the year and producer, including all milled components, with all parts properly Waffenamted(Eagle/1) and the Eagle/Swaztikas being unmarred. Importantly, all serialized components show matching numbers, including the lower comb of the buttstock and the barrel channel of the handguard. A superb candidate for having been brought back by a GI returning from the war, K98ks in all-original, matching condition, are rapidly disappearing from the market place and this weapon would be a superb addition to the most advanced collection.Condition:Near excellent condition, the rifle has seen no restoration or refinish, with originally thin bluing naturally fading to a powder blue-tinged hue. There are light traces of oxidation, but no rust or deep pitting and the milling marks on the metal are distinct. Markings are well-struck, correct and no import mark is present. As stated above, all numbered components are matching, to include the handguard and buttstock, with the bayonet lug and cleaning rod unnumbered. The furniture is in correspondingly near excellent condition, having dings, scrapes, mild laminate separation and a tight hairline crack extending from the the wrist beneath the receiver on the right side of the stock. Mechanically flawless, the bore is very good but should clean to better, having strong, sharp rifling beneath lint

title: For Sale:  Scarce WWII Gustloff 98k Nazi German Mauser bcd 42 1942 K98 K98k Rifle Matching
postcontent: early production Gustloff-Werke K98k...this all-correct Mauser was produced by Gustloff for the German military in 1942. One of the last companies offered a contract by the Third Reich to produce this iconic arm, Gustloff notably maintained higher standards of build quality than the other producers throughout the war. The rifle has typical features for the year and producer, including all milled components, with all parts properly Waffenamted(Eagle/1) and the Eagle/Swaztikas being unmarred. Importantly, all serialized components show matching numbers, including the lower comb of the buttstock and the barrel channel of the handguard. A superb candidate for having been brought back by a GI returning from the war, K98ks in all-original, matching condition, are rapidly disappearing from the market place and this weapon would be a superb addition to the most advanced collection.Condition:Near excellent condition, the rifle has seen no restoration or refinish, with originally thin bluing naturally fading to a powder blue-tinged hue. There are light traces of oxidation, but no rust or deep pitting and the milling marks on the metal are distinct. Markings are well-struck, correct and no import mark is present. As stated above, all numbered components are matching, to include the handguard and buttstock, with the bayonet lug and cleaning rod unnumbered. The furniture is in correspondingly near excellent condition, having dings, scrapes, mild laminate separation and a tight hairline crack extending from the the wrist beneath the receiver on the right side of the stock. Mechanically flawless, the bore is very good but should clean to better, having strong, sharp rifling beneath lint, residue and a hint of frost.
